Flight from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke off their connections with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged until recently to the latter category.
Their economic and political failure was largely due to - actively supported by Russia - secessionist movements that tried to keep both countries in the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts broke out in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping troops" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn hot.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions – because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to make a breakthrough towards a market economy and democracy.
This was also contributed to by the European Union's "neighborhood policy".
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
One state already in danger of failing, Georgia has meanwhile turned to the West.
The success of the various "color revolutions" in the former countries of the Soviet block also led to a change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms with the goal of drawing closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems, making it unsuitable for investment.
Estland was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, yet its economy was growing.
In North-East Estonia with its predominantly Russian population, who had settled here during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called „autonomy movement“.
As Estonia resisted, Russia introduced sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
Taxes were levied on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy in the direction of the West.
On the other hand, Western Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic States - Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia - and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU allowed Estonian products to find new markets, and so Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries and joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
However, Georgia appeared as a partner less attractive than the Baltic States; the 1990s were marked by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, with two regions - Abkhazia and South Ossetia - essentially breaking away with Russian support.
The country has given its best to forget its desolate past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and actively striving to bring the country forward.
Due to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – which is probably the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is concerned with easing tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to prevent reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to some extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also of importance.
Estonia has – at the time of its independence and again during the latest crisis, with the relocation of a monument from the Soviet era – shown that one can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has good reason to hope that it will achieve a true independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is threatened by Russia more than Estonia or even Georgia ever have been?
The lack of reform progress is partly the result of the secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That the industrialized region of Transnistria – whose Russian and Ukrainian-speaking population feared that the majority of Moldovans of Romanian descent planned to establish closer ties with Romania – would secede from Moldova, dealt the country a severe blow at the very beginning of its independence.
It was followed by a civil war, and in the year 1992, Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they are still today.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that lawlessness and corruption reign there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to take an interest in finding a solution and withdrawing Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has appealed to the EU observer mission Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems to the West that it lacks current insights into the situation in Moldova.
In April, for example, the EU and the US learned about a proposed peace agreement only through a report leaked in Germany.
This, it seems, would favor Russia, as Moldova is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity within it.
If Russia has thus outsmarted the West, this would be a dire precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
